.TH cvslock 1 "October 1998" Unix "User Manuals"
.SH NAME
.PP
cvslock \- lock CVS repositories
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B cvslock
[-q] [-p \fIpid\fP] [-d \fICVS root\fP] [-R|-W] [-u|-s|-c \fICommand\fP] \fIdirectory\fP
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.B cvslock
is used to lock a tree starting at \fIdirectory\fP in your CVS
repository during low-level manipulation or inspection.
.PP
There are various modes of operation: You can use the -s or -c
options to cause
.B cvslock
to spawn a sub-shell or a shell command from which you can safely
access the source repository.  
.PP
You can also use
.B cvslock
to lock and unlock CVS repositories from shell scripts; in this case
you'll want to use the -p option to specify the process ID which is
written to the lock files' names.
.PP
The default when given no options is to acquire a persistant read
lock.
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
.IP "-q"
This option tells 
.B cvslock
to shut up and not print any diagnostic messages to stdout.  This is
most useful when using the program in conjunction with, e.g.,
.BR  rsync (1) .
.IP "-p \fIpid\fP"
The CVS lock files generated by this utility have the current
process ID in their name to distinguish them from lock files
generated by other tools such as 
.B cvs 
itself or concurrent sessions
of 
.BR cvslock .
Use this option to force
.B cvslock
to use a specific pid.  This is in most useful from shell
scripts.
.IP "-d \fICVS root\fP"
This optional argument tells
.B cvslock
where your CVS repository's root is.  If no -d switch is given,
.B cvslock
will fall back to the 
.B CVSROOT
environment variable.  Note that
.B cvslock
only works on local repositories, so don't try to access pserver or
rsh-accessible remote repositories this way.
.IP "-R"
This switch tells 
.B cvslock
to acquire a lock for safe reading of the repository.
.IP "-W"
This switch tells
.B cvslock
to acquire a write lock on the repository.
.IP "-s"
When invoked with this option, 
.B cvslock
will invoke the user's login shell as determined by the
.B SHELL
environment variable after locking the repository.  After the user
has left that shell, 
.B cvslock
will drop the locks.
.IP "-c \fICommand\fP"
This option is similar to the -s option, with the difference that
.B cvslock
will execute the shell command given on the command line instead of
giving the user an interactive shell.
.IP "-u"
When given this option, 
.B cvslock
will try to drop a previously created lock on the repository in
question.  Using this option together with the -s or -c options is
an error.  The use of -p is highly recommended in conjunction with
this option!
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
.PP
.B cvslock
spits out some diagnostics to the standard error stream.  It's exit
value is zero if and only if the locking operation requested by the
user could be performed successfully.  Note that \fIno\fP
diagnostics about the exit value of commands executed through the
.B -c
switch are given.
.SH BUGS
.PP
The signal handling is not too well-tested and may be broken.
.PP
If you try to create the same lock several times, you will get funny
effects due to the error recovery
.B cvslock
tries to do.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
Version Management with CVS
.PP
.BR rsync (1),
.BR system (3),
.BR cvs (1)
